Trump‚Äôs SEC Plans To Change Crypto Policies And May Stop Enforcement Temporarily: Reuters   Trump‚Äôs SEC Is Reviewing Some Crypto Enforcement Cases That Are Currently In Court: Reuters

*TRUMP'S SEC TO OVERHAUL CRYPTO POLICY, MAY FREEZE ENFORCEMENT: RTRS  *In the first few days of the new administration, the SEC is expected to begin a review of those court cases and potentially freeze some litigation that does not involve allegations of fraud, said two of the sources. Some of those cases could eventually be withdrawn.

James Seyffart (ETF Research analyst at Bloomberg Intelligence) on Altcoin ETFs in 2025: Blockworks  *James Seyffart said that SSAs with exchanges like Coinbase, Kraken, could satisfy the SEC's concerns about market manipulation, but the SEC has historically leaned on futures markets for approval and also SEC have lawsuits against these exchanges.   *He also said their are no SOL ETF deadlines because the SEC just didn't acknowledge filings so they basically denied them outright. He suggested that a change in SEC leadership, particularly under a potential Trump administration, could expedite the process. However, he cautioned against overly optimistic market expectations, noting that even with a more crypto-friendly SEC chair like Paul Atkins, the approval process could take until 2026. While he believes the approval of altcoin ETFs is a matter of "when, not if," he does not guarantee it will happen in 2025.  ** *He pointed out that if issuers file much of Solana ETF filings right after Gary Gensler steps down and a new administration takes office, the SEC's acknowledgment of these filings within a couple of weeks could provide a clearer timeline for approval.** However, he questioned whether the SEC would prioritize these filings while other divisions still have open cases labeling these assets as securities. SEC might drop lawsuits against exchanges or settle them, which could pave the way for a more favorable regulatory environment. This would depend on the new leadership's willingness to resolve these legal disputes and align the SEC's internal divisions.  ** *Seyffart also highlighted the irony **of SEC Chair Gary Gensler‚Äôs past involvement in teaching blockchain and crypto at MIT, contrasting it with his stringent regulatory stance under the Biden administration. He predicted that while a new administration might reduce regulatory headwinds, it won‚Äôt be a "free-for-all," as the SEC will still target bad actors and enforce rules.  *On 2025 Outlook: He predicts trump will repeal SAB 121 and US will not sell any more of BTC they currently holds. (He is less optimistic on the Strategic Bitcoin Reserve, He don't think Reserve helps all that much)

*Steve Witkoff (top negotiator for the war in Ukraine) has been involved in the talks for a deal, Witkoff could also be a beneficiary if the deal goes through World Liberty Financial: Witkoff & his two sons are co-founders of the business, along with the Trumps. An administration official denied Witkoff's involvement and said he is in the process of divesting from his business interests. Witkoff has said he stepped away from the company after taking on his White House role.

*For the Trump family, a stake in BinanceUS would give them the opportunity to participate in the potential revival of a onetime competitor to Coinbase.

*Binance executives saw a potential legal playbook in the saga of Justin Sun who invested $30M in November in World Liberty Financial becoming its largest investor as he faced civil charges from SEC. Last month, the SEC asked a court to pause its fraud lawsuit against Sun and three of his businesses. **After Sun's investment, Binance executives internally debated following the same route: a cash infusion into World Liberty Financial in exchange for a pardon for Zhao, the person familiar with the discussions said: WSJ**

Those tariffs would last for only up to 150 days, after which the law requires Congressional action to extend.  ***Sec. 232 tariffs, which President Trump has already used for steel, aluminum, and autos, could be broadened to cover other sectors. We already expect additional sectoral tariffs (pharmaceuticals, semiconductors/electronics, etc) and uncertainty regarding the IEEPA-based tariffs could lead the White House to put more emphasis on sectoral tariffs**, where there is much less legal uncertainty: GS  *In conclusion, the bulk of Trump's tariffs - which clearly are now targeting just a handful of trading partners such as China, EU and Japan - can and most likely will stay, even if SCOTUS does not void the trade court ruling on appeal: GS

Too much misinformation about Powell's speech going around, so here's the short summary: INFINITYHEDGE   ***Powell left the door open for Sept. Rate Cut but signaled it won't be the start of aggressive easing.**  *On the labor market, Powell said ‚Äùthe labor market appears to be in balance, it is a curious kind of balance that results from a marked slowing in both the supply of & demand for workers. This unusual situation suggests that downside risks to employment are rising. And if those risks materialize, they can do so quickly in the form of sharply higher layoffs.  *On inflation, Powell said: The effects of tariffs on consumer prices are now clearly visible. We expect those effects to accumulate over coming months, with high uncertainty about timing & amounts... A reasonable base case is that the effects will be a one-time shift in the price level. Ofc, ‚Äúone-time‚Äù does not mean ‚Äúall at once.‚Äù It will continue to take time for tariff increases to work their way through supply chains...& Ofc we cannot take the stability of inflation expectations for granted. Come what may, we will not allow a one-time increase in the price level to become an ongoing inflation problem.  ***In Conclusion, Powell said: In the near term, risks to inflation are tilted to the upside, and risks to employment to the downside‚Äîa challenging situation**... Our policy rate is now 100 basis points closer to neutral than it was a year ago, and the stability of the unemployment rate & other labor market measures allows us to proceed carefully as we consider changes to our policy stance. Nonetheless, with policy in restrictive territory, the baseline outlook **and the shifting balance of risks may warrant adjusting our policy stance**.  **<Policy Framework Change>:** (we covered it already here: https://t.me/infinityhedge/26042 before Powell's Speech but still misinformation spreading, & please don't blindly trust twitter influencers)  Powell said the Fed has adopted a new framework, Key Changes: ‚Ü≥ removed ELB ‚Ü≥ dropped the policy of intentionally allowing inflation to run moderately above 2% to compensate for past periods when it was below 2%.  ‚Ü≥ removed "shortfalls" term that focused only on unemployment being too high. {While Powell said they still believe employment can run above estimates without necessarily creating risks to price stability}. (this was kindof a communication fix) ‚Ü≥ The revised policy framework now more closely aligns with the original 2012 (balanced approach).  **In short: The Fed moved away from 2020 framework back toward 2012 framework and Now is less tolerant of sustained inflation above 2%.** (These changes likely won‚Äôt affect near-term policy decisions).  Opinion: <@infinityhedge> ‚Ü≥ By returning to a focus on price stability and a 2% inflation target, this implies that all concerned should prepare for higher rates for longer despite a rising probability of near-term rate cuts: RSM  *Deutsche, Barclays, BNP, GS, JPM, Nomura expects a Fed Rate Cut in September.   Tldr: Powell was cautiously dovish with hawkish undertone but was essentially neutral And rate decision will depend on the August employment and CPI reports.
